By the Pythagorean Theorem, $AC^2=AB^2+BC^2$, so $(2x-6)^2=90^2+x^2$.  Expanding, we have $4x^2-24x+36=8100+x^2$, or $3x^2-24x-8064=0$.  Dividing both sides by 3, we have $x^2-8x-2688=0$.  Factoring, we get $(x-56)(x+48)=0$, so $x=56$ (we discard the negative solution).  Thus, $AC=2(56)-6=106$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (0,106);
B = (0,0);
C = (90,0);
D = (B + reflect(A,C)*(B))/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$90$", (B + C)/2, S);
label("$90$", (A + B)/2, W);
label("$90$", (A + D)/2, NW);
label("$x$", (B + C)/2, S);
label("$90$", (B + A)/2, W);
label("$2x - 6$", (A + C)/2, NE);
[/asy]

Since $AD$ is an angle bisector, we have $\angle BAD = \angle DAC$.  Since $\angle ABC = 90^\circ$, we have $\angle BAD + \angle DAC = 90^\circ$, so $\angle BAD = \angle DAC = 45^\circ$.  Thus, triangle $ABD$ is a 45-45-90 triangle, so $BD = AB = 90$.

The area of triangle $ADC$ is equal to $\frac{1}{2}(CD)(AD)$.  Since $CD = BC - BD = 56 - 90 = -34$, we have $CD = 34$.  Since $AD$ is the hypotenuse of triangle $ABD$, we have $AD = 90\sqrt{2}$.  Thus, the area of triangle $ADC$ is $\frac{1}{2}(34)(90\sqrt{2}) = 1530\sqrt{2} \approx \boxed{2162}$.

